[02:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Superpowers version is better than the version without using Superpowers. We\'ll go through the code a bit later on in the video, but first, let\'s go through how I did this. So, after you install the Superpowers plugin, we should now have some new slash commands like'

[02:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'brainstorm, execute plan, and write the plan what to write the plan from the brainstorm. Now, we only actually need this command since Superpowers will direct us to the next stage at the end of a previous one. So, let\'s run this,'

[02:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and we\'ll paste in a prompt. We\'re going to hit enter, and now it loads the brainstorming skill and begins to understand the current project. And here it\'s going to ask me some questions to further improve the plan. So, I\'m going to say React plus Vite, and then I\'ll'

[02:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'say step-by-step for the article generation. And now it\'s asked me to confirm the structure of the architecture, which I think looks good. It also asks about the layouts, and then asks about the endpoint and server logic. So, after I\'ve answered all the'

[02:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'questions, it then goes ahead to create a plan, which it\'s now put inside this directory. And if we take a look at the plan, we can see it\'s very detailed, giving an overview, the stack, the structure, as well as design, layout, API endpoint, and much more. In fact,'

[03:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this is very similar to what Claude code would give us if it was writing its own plan. But the next step is where things get interesting. So, after I confirm the plan and say I\'m ready for implementation, it then goes ahead and'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'writes another implementation plan. It does this by first looking at the original design plan that we created, and it breaks this down into smaller, more manageable chunks of tasks that can be completed by parallel sub agents. So,'

[03:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now it\'s written another plan, and it\'s saved it to the plans directory again. And if we take a look at that one, we can see instead of giving a detailed overview of the project and architecture, it splits things up into tasks. So, we have one task here to'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'scaffold the project, and it has some steps inside those tasks. We have another task here to create Vit M React client skeleton, and again it has some steps. And this keeps going on with every task that\'s needed to complete the'

[03:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'project. From here, Superpowers asks me to pick an approach. Do I want the sub-agent driven approach or the parallel session approach? This approach uses a separate sub-agent for each task without any human confirmation. This'

[04:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'approach will create another session from the plan session, complete the tasks in batches, and then check with me, so the human, if I\'m happy with the batch it\'s completed before it continues. Now, for the sake of speed, I\'m going to go with the sub-agent'

[04:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'driven approach. And now it\'s gone ahead and created the tasks that need to be completed for this project. Now, unfortunately, these tasks look different from the previous tasks because I forgot to record the screen the first time. So, I\'ve gone ahead and started again, but I used the exact same'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'prompt. So, what\'s happening now is that each sub-agent is first creating a test, so it\'s writing a test that\'s going to fail, and then it writes the minimal code to make that test pass. And then when it\'s finished working on the'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'feature, it verifies the feature passes the requirements that were specified in the plan, and then moves on to check the quality of the code, which checks if it\'s clean, well-built, and maintainable. So, now it\'s finished most of the tasks, it\'s now going to test'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'everything it\'s done. And here we have it, it\'s completed all the tasks, and it even found one bug in the process that it was able to fix. And if we take a look at the code, it\'s split by server and source. I\'m assuming source is the front-end or client. We have some'

[05:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'components in here, so article tab, download tab, etc. If we take a look at the pipeline progress, we have stages and an object, a TypeScript interface. Now, it looks like it\'s using some kind of CSS in JS for the styling, and in'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hindsight I should have specified to use Tailwind, but this is fine. And check this out, this is something Opus Plan mode wouldn\'t do by default. You can see through every step of the way Superpower has made a Git commit. From scaffolding'

[05:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the project to adding the CLI wrapper and adding Hono and everything in between. So, if I check the Git status, there\'s nothing for me to commit because the branch is clean, which is much less work on my part. Now, you may be looking'

[05:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'at this and wondering where the test files are. I\'ll talk about that later. So, if I\'m being honest, I think Superpowers is an impressive project. I love the fact that it focuses on skills. I think it has 14, which do so many different things from brainstorming to'

[06:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'planning to implementing and even reviewing the code afterwards. I love the focus on TDD, specifically red-green TDD, where it writes the tests first so they fail, making them red, and then writes minimal code to pass them. But,'

[06:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sometimes this doesn\'t always work because the agent chooses not to do that. Take a look at this. So, here we can see the writing plan skill explicitly set TDD, and for some reason Claude chose not to do it. I asked it to'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'confirm that and it said, "Yes, it\'s on me. The skill says TDD and I still don\'t do it." And asked it, "Why did you not do it?" And then it says it focused on shipping quickly over following the process. I\'m not sure exactly why this'

[06:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'happened for a state-of-the-art model, but it just goes to show that you shouldn\'t blindly accept what the model does. It\'s important to read through the plan and make sure it does what you expect it to do. This is one of the reasons why I don\'t think I\'ll be using'

[06:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Superpowers for every single one of my projects or feature requirements, purely because they\'re quite small. And if I have a small feature I want to add, I\'m happy to go back and forth with Claude to plan this out, write a plan document,'

[07:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and then wipe the context to execute that plan. But, if I do find myself in the situation where I\'m implementing multiple features, which does happen from time to time, then Superpowers is a'

[07:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'great tool to use just because it\'s very good at breaking down complex requirements into chunks that can be completed by sub-agents. And yes, the Claude code tasks feature can kind of do'

[07:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'this, but I love the fact that Superpowers creates a plan for this instead of going ahead to implement the code. Now, how does Superpowers compare to something like Beets or Spec Pit or the whole spec-driven development'

[07:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'architecture? For me, it seems like a more simple version of planning out before executing. Of course, not as simple as something like Ralph, but maybe in between something like Ralph and Beets. But, it seems like to me there are more and more tools like this'

[08:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'helping people to write better code with their AI agent. Now, this is a good thing, but everyone is different and I think it\'s good to take a bit from here, a bit from there, and end up making your own workflow that is perfect for you.'

[08:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
